{"name":"Stearic acid","desc":"Stearic acid (/ˈstɪərɪk/ STEER-ik, /ˈstɪ.æ.rɪk/ stee-ARR-ik) is a saturated fatty acid with an 18-carbon chain and has the IUPAC name octadecanoic acid. It is a waxy solid and its chemical formula is C17H35CO2H. Its name comes from the Greek word στέαρ \"stéar\", which means tallow. The salts and esters of stearic acid are called stearates. As its ester, stearic acid is one of the most common saturated fatty acids found in nature following palmitic acid. The triglyceride derived from three molecules of stearic acid is called stearin.","images":[{"alt":"Skeletal formula of stearic acid","src":"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b3/Stearic_acid.svg/240px-Stearic_acid.svg.png"},{"alt":"Ball-and-stick model of stearic acid","src":"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Stearic-acid-3D-balls.png/240px-Stearic-acid-3D-balls.png"},{"alt":"Stearic acid","src":"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6b/Stearins%C3%A4ure_auf_Uhrglas.jpg/200px-Stearins%C3%A4ure_auf_Uhrglas.jpg"}],"link":"/wiki/Stearic_acid","Preferred IUPAC name":"Octadecanoic acid\nOctadecanoic acid","Lipid numbers":"Stearic acid\nC18:0 (Lipid numbers)","CAS Number":"57-11-4 Y","3D model (JSmol)":"Interactive image","ChemSpider":"5091 N","DrugBank":"DB03193 Y","ECHA InfoCard":"100.000.285","EC Number":"200-313-4","IUPHAR/BPS":"3377","PubChem CID":"5281","RTECS number":"WI2800000","Chemical formula":"<span title=\"Carbon\">C</span><sub>18</sub><span title=\"Hydrogen\">H</span><sub>36</sub><span title=\"Oxygen\">O</span><sub>2</sub>","Molar mass":"284.48 g·mol−1","Appearance":"White solid","Odor":"Pungent, oily","Density":"0.9408 g/cm<sup>3</sup> (20 &#xB0;C)<sup id=\"cite_ref-crc_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-crc-2\">[2]</a></sup><br>\n0.847 g/cm<sup>3</sup> (70 &#xB0;C)","Melting point":"69.3 °C (156.7 °F; 342.4 K) [2]","Boiling point":"361 °C (682 °F; 634 K)\ndecomposes\n232 °C (450 °F; 505 K)\nat 15 mmHg[2]","Solubility in 